INSERT INTO html VALUES (3,'homepage','home page','<h3>San Francisco Bay Vanguard 15 Fleet</h3>\n<small>\nIf you are looking for an active and competitive dinghy fleet in the San Francisco Bay  Area, then the Vanguard 15 is your best bet. Our fleet began with 8 boats ordered in April, 1998. There are now more than 50 boats in Northern California. For Bay Area residents, a fleet of 30 boats has been established at the Treasure Island Sailing Center. There are also growing fleets in the Los Angeles and Seattle areas.<p>\n<p>The Thursday Night Vanguard Races are now legendary:  20 boats on the line each night for an average of 6 races.   You\'d be hard-pressed to find that kind of action anywhere else in the Bay Area.<p>\nThe boat is both exciting, yet easy for a couple to race.  Our fleet members range from collegiate all-americans to big-boat sailors looking for tighter action and more tactical situations. \nWith over 30 events scheduled for 2004, there are plenty of opportunities to sail a Vanguard.   Sign up for the mailing list to find out more about our fleet.\n</small>',20040319095239);
INSERT INTO html VALUES (4,'seasonscoring','2004 Season Scoring','<h3>2004 San Francisco Season Championship Scoring</h3>\n<li>50% of the races races (30 of approx 60) must be sailed to qualify.</li>\n<li>In order to reward participation, the more races you do, the more throwouts you get.  For each race you do beyond 75%, you get 1 additional throwout, so your score cannot go down once you\'ve done 75% of the races.  The number of throwouts is determined as such:<br><br>\n0-50% of races sailed:   10% throwouts (ie: 1 in 10, 2 in 20, etc...)<BR>\n50-75% of races sailed   30% throwouts (ie: 3 of the next 10, 6 of the next 20)<BR>\n75%-100% of races sailed: 100% throwout (you\'ll drop a lower score from earlier in the season)<BR>\n<br>\n<li>Your score is computed by dividing the total number of boats you beat in each race plus one by the total number of boats you have sailed against.  For instance if you only sailed in three regattas where there were 5 total races and you scored a 2nd of 17, 8th of 17, 3rd of 5, 12th of 13 and 3rd of 13; your score would look like this:<br>\n<pre>\n (16 + 10 + 3 +  2 + 11)<BR>\n------------------------- = 42 / 65 = 0.65<BR>\n (17 + 17 + 5 + 13 + 13)\n</pre>\n<li>If you don\'t sail in a regatta or part of a regatta (a DNS), it\ndoesn\'t get counted against you. This means that you don\'t get a 0/12 if you\ncouldn\'t make a regatta or a race in a regatta where there were 12 boats sailing.</li>\n<li>A DSQ results in a 0 / (# of boats) for that race added to your score.  These cannot be discarded as throwouts if you reach the throwout level previously mentioned.</li>\n<li>A DNF will be averaged between the remaining boats that didn\'t finish a race. For instance, in a race where 10 boats started and only 5 boats finished, the 5 DNFs will be given a 3/10. This number is reached by adding up the remaining points that could have been assigned if all boats finished.<br><pre>\n(5+4+3+2+1)<BR>\n--------------------  = 15/5 = 3<BR>\n        5\n</pre>',20040525094228);
