INSERT INTO txt VALUES (69,'<b> 2004 VANGUARD 15 RED STRIPE FLEET CHAMPS </b>\n<p>\nTreasure Island Sailing Center \n<p>\nMay 22-23, 2004 \n<p>\nNOTICE OF RACE \n<p>\n1. Rules \n<p>\nThis regatta shall be governed by The Racing Rules of Sailing (RRS);\n(except as any of these are modified by the Sailing Instructions),\nand by the Sailing Instructions. All competitors are required to wear\na life jacket or other adequate personal flotation device while\nracing. Competitors in all classes are required to carry a bowline of\nat least fifteen feet attached to a towing point while racing. \n<p>\n2. Eligibility \n<p>\nAll sailors must complete a medical liability waiver form for TISC\nprior to sailing. Please sign up on the web site so that organizers\nmay plan food and drinks etc. \n<p>\n3. Entry \n<p>\nEntry forms are not required. The entry fee is $45, less $5 with\nproof of current USSA membership. Registration will begin at 1030\nhours and close at 1130 hours on May 22, 2004. All boats must pay or\nhave paid current annual fleet dues of $25 at registration. \n<p>\n4. Schedule \n<p>\nThe first Warning Signal Saturday is scheduled for 12:00. A Sailors\'\nMeeting will be held at 11:30 hours on Saturday, May 22, 2004. \n<p>\n5. Sailing Instructions \n<p>\nThe Sailing Instructions will be available at the check-in before the\nSailors\' Meeting, while an unofficial copy may be found on the V15\nweb site by Thursday, May 20, 2004. \n<p>\n6. Scoring System \n<p>\nThe Low Point Scoring System, Appendix A of the Racing Rules, will\napply. Twelve races are scheduled for the V-15 class. One race will\nconstitute a series. \n<p>\n7. Racing Area \n<p>\nThe intended race area will be set in Clipper Cove utilizing round\norange marks. \n<p>\n8. Berthing & Trailer Storage \n<p>\nAll boats must be stored clear of aisles and driveways, boats that\nare not TISC tenants may be subject to TISC usage fees. Included in\nthe regatta fees are $10/boat donation to TISC. \n<p>\n9. Social \n<p>\nAll competitors are welcome to attend a BBQ with soda and beer on\nSaturday night free of charge, and to attend a trophy ceremony\nfollowing the conclusion of racing on Sunday. ');
INSERT INTO txt VALUES (70,'\r\n\r\n2004 VANGUARD 15 RED STRIPE FLEET CHAMPS \r\n\r\nTreasure Island Sailing Center \r\n\r\nMay 22-23, 2004 \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\nSAILING INSTRUCTIONS \r\n\r\n1. Rules \r\n\r\n1.1 The regatta shall be governed by the \n\nRacing Rules of Sailing (RRS2001-2004). \r\n\r\n1.2 Competitors attention is drawn to: \r\n\r\nRRS 1.2 \n\n Fundamental Rules  Life Saving Equipment and Personal Buoyancy: A\nboat shall carry adequate \n\nlife-saving equipment for all persons on board, including one item\nready for \n\nimmediate use, unless class rules make some other provision. Each\ncompetitor is \n\nindividually responsible for wearing personal buoyancy adequate for\nthe \n\nconditions. \r\n\r\nRRS \n\n1.1 Helping those in Danger \r\n\r\nRRS 4 \n\nDecision to Race \r\n\r\nSI 17 \n\nInterference with Other Vessels \r\n\r\n1.3 Competitors shall wear personal buoyancy \n\nwhile racing, the Y flag will not be displayed. This changes RRS\n40. \r\n\r\n1.4 All boats shall have tied to their boat, \n\nand accessible, a fifteen foot tow line. \r\n\r\n1.5 A boat that retires from a race prior to \n\nfinishing or does not intend to compete in a race shall notify the\nRace \n\nCommittee either before leaving the course area or immediately after\narriving \n\nashore. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n2. \n\nEntries \r\n\r\nEligible boats \n\nshall complete registration with the TISC Race Office from 1030 to\n1100 hrs May \n\n22, 2004. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n3. \n\nCommunication with competitors \r\n\r\n3.1 Official Notices will be posted on the \n\nOfficial Notice Board located across from the office door. \r\n\r\n3.2 Any changes in the Sailing Instructions \n\nwill be posted by 1030 hours on the day they are to take effect. \r\n\r\n3.3 Questions regarding the Sailing \n\nInstructions may be submitted in writing to the Race Committee.\nQuestions and \n\nwritten responses will be posted on the Official Notice Board. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n4. \n\nNumber &amp; Schedule of Races \r\n\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n\n4.1 Twelve races \n\nare scheduled for racing on Bravo course, with six races on Saturday\nand six \n\nraces on Sunday. \r\n\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n\n4.2 The First \n\nWarning Signal each day will be at 1200 hrs. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n5. \n\nRacing Area \r\n\r\n5.1 The intended \n\nracing area for the Alpha Course will be around inflatable marks in\nClipper \n\nCove \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n6. The Course \r\n\r\n6.1 The courses \n\nand marks are described on Attachment A  Official description of\nmarks and courses. \r\n\r\n\r\n6.2 A placard \n\ndesignating the course will be displayed from the Race Committee\nsignal boat \n\nprior to the class warning signal. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n7. Changes of \n\nCourse after the Start \r\n\r\nA \n\nchange of course after the start will be signaled before the leading\nboat has \n\nbegun the leg, although the new mark may not then be in position. Any\nmark to \n\nbe rounded after rounding the new mark may be relocated to maintain\nthe \n\noriginal course configuration. When in a subsequent change of course\na new mark \n\nis replaced, it will be replaced with an original mark. This changes\nRRS 33. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n8. The Start \r\n\r\nRaces \n\nwill be started using the 3-minute starting sequence. Flags will\nprobably not be used to signal time intervals. An \n\nexplanation of the 3-minute whistle sequence follows: \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\nWarning:   Multiple, \n\nShort Whistle Blasts \r\n\r\n3 \n\nMinuets:   3 Long \n\nWhistle Blasts \r\n\r\n2 \n\nMinuets:   2 Long \n\nWhistle Blasts \r\n\r\n1 \n\nMinute, 30 Seconds: 1 Long, 3 \n\nShort Whistle Blasts \r\n\r\n1 \n\nMinute:   1 Long \n\nWhistle Blast \r\n\r\n30 \n\nSeconds:   3 Short \n\nWhistle Blasts \r\n\r\n20 \n\nSeconds:   2 Short \n\nWhistle Blasts \r\n\r\n10 \n\nSeconds:   1 Short \n\nWhistle Blast \r\n\r\n5,4,3,2,1 \n\nSeconds:  1 Short Whistle Blast/Second \r\n\r\nStart:    1 \n\nLong Whistle Blast \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\nA \n\nboat shall not start later than 4 minutes after her starting signal. \r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n9. Recalls \r\n\r\n9.1 After the \n\nstarting signal, the Race Committee may hail the sail number(s) of\nthe boat(s) \n\nidentified on the course side of the starting by loud hailer. The\nfailure of a \n\nhail, the failure of a boat to hear the hail or the order of the\nhails shall \n\nnot be grounds for redress. It is the responsibility of the\ncompetitors to \n\nstart correctly. \r\n\r\n9.2 A new Warning \n\nSignal may be sounded immediately after a general recall. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n10. Alternative Penalties \r\n\r\nThe &quot;720 Turns Penalty&quot; is modified as \n\nfollows: &quot;The penalty for a Part 2 rule broken inside the\ntwo-length zone \n\nof a mark, shall be a 720 degrees penalty as prescribed by this rule\nwithout \n\nmodification. The penalty for a Part 2 rule broken outside the two\nlength zone \n\nof a mark, shall be a 360 degree turn. For the purpose of this rule,\na finish \n\nline mark is considered a mark, however, a starting line mark is not. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n11. \n\nThe Finish \r\n\r\nThe finish line will be between the PRO stationed on the \n\ncommittee boat ad the finishing pin (same mark as the starting pin).\nThe PRO has the right to assign finishing \n\nposition (s) with no prior signals or announcements. Race sequences\nshall be \n\nstarted promptly following the finish of the final competitor of the\nrace prior \n\nor the decision of the PRO. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n11.1 One \n\nMinute Rule  I Flag. At the PROs \n\ndiscretion, the one-minute rule may be put into effect using either\ncode I or \n\nby announcement of the PRO. When code \n\nflag I is displayed (or announced), any yacht that crosses the\nstart line \n\nafter the 1 minute whistle signal, prior to the starting signal, will\nbe \n\nrequired to sail around one end of the starting line and restart. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n12. Time Limit for Each Race \r\n\r\nThe \n\nTime Limit for each race will be 2 hours. A boat failing to finish\nwithin 30 \n\nminutes after the first boat in her class will be scored Did Not\nFinish by \n\nthe Race Committee. This changes RRS 35. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n13. Protests \r\n\r\n Competitors are required to hail \n\nProtest and the offending boats sail number immediately after the\nincident \n\nwhen they intend to file a protest. \n\nUpon finishing the Protester is required to inform the Race Committee \n\nand the Protestee that they intend to proceed with a protest.\nProtests will be conducted using the 3 \n\nMinute Justice System. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n The 3 \n\nMinute Justice System requires each party in the protest to pick one\ncompetitor \n\nas a jury member. Those two jury \n\nmembers will then select a 3rd jury member to complete the \n\njury. Each competitor is given 3 minutes \n\nto present their view of the incident and the applicable rules.\nAfter each competitor has presented their \n\nview, each competitor can call 1 witness to present their view of the \n\nsituation. The 3-person jury will \n\ndecide the outcome. All decisions of \n\nthe competitor jury are final. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n14. Scoring \r\n\r\n14.1 The Low Point \n\nScoring System of RRS A2 will apply. \r\n\r\n14.2 One race will \n\nconstitute a series. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n15. Restricted Areas \r\n\r\n15.1 For safety \n\nreasons, boats shall not pass through the areas bound by the line of\nbuoys \n\nalong the shore of Yerba Buena Islands and the closest point ashore: \r\n\r\n15.2 Boats may not \n\npass between the dinghy ramp and its buoys. \r\n\r\n15.3 The above-mentioned \n\nareas are defined as obstructions. \r\n\r\n15.4 A boat that \n\nbreaks this rule may not correct her error and shall retire. This\nchanges RRS \n\n28.1. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n16. Prizes \r\n\r\nPrizes \n\nwill be awarded at the end of the regatta to both members of the\ncrews placing \n\n1st  3rd in the Varsity and Non-Varsity divisions. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n17. Berthing \n\nand Trailer Storage \r\n\r\n Overnight mast-up storage is \n\nallowed. At the end of the regatta all \n\nboats must be properly stored in their assigned spaces. Please make\nsure to store each boat in an \n\norderly, clean fashion. Dollies are to \n\nbe returned to the proper storage areas. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n Each day a \n\nrepresentative from each boat shall assist in the launch &amp;\nstorage of RC \n\nand chase boats, marks, horns, and other equipment. They shall also\nassist in lock down of cranes, fences, bridals, \n\nhoses, etc. Trash and items to be recycled are to be placed \n\ninto the large cans provided for the purpose. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n18. Interference with Other Vessels \r\n\r\nBoats \n\nshall not impede the passage of all vessels (except RC) while racing.\nRule 9 of \n\nthe Inland Rules of the Road applies with respect to all shipping\ntraffic on \n\nSan Francisco Bay and its tributaries. A violation of Rule 9 is\nsubject to \n\nprotest by any competitor and the race committee. Compliance with the\nRRS 60-63 \n\nwill not be required with respect to a protest involving a Rule 9\ninfraction. A \n\nviolation of Rule 9 may not be exonerated by an alternate penalty.\nAny \n\ncomplaint received by the race committee from the United States Coast\nGuard or \n\nthe captain or bar pilot of any ship that has sounded five blasts on\nits horn \n\nduring the course of a race shall result in an automatic protest by\nthe race \n\ncommittee if the captain, bar pilot or Coast Guard identifies an\noffending boat \n\nby sail number. In any case where a ship has sounded five blasts on\nits horn, a \n\npresumption shall be created at the protest hearing that the\nprotested yacht(s) \n\nhas (have) violated Rule 9 and the protested yacht(s) shall have the\nburden of \n\nproving that it did not impede the progress of the ship. Race\ncommittee chase boats may patrol the \n\nrace course from time to time and may hail boats to alter course to\navoid \n\nimpeding ship traffic. Failure of any boat to comply with the hail of\nthe race \n\ncommittee shall result in an automatic protest by the race committee.\nA protest of a Rule 9 infraction by a \n\ncompetitor may be made at any time prior to the conclusion of the\nregatta, but \n\nnot more than 24 hours after the incident. A protest by the race\ncommittee for \n\nan infraction of Rule 9 may be made at any time up to two days after\nthe \n\nconclusion of the regatta. The Race Committee will cooperate and\nprovide \n\nrelevant information to any investigations of violations of Rule 9 by\nthe Coast \n\nGuard or other competent governmental authority. \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCOURSES &amp; \n\nMARKS \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPLACARD \n\nROUNDING ORDER \r\n\r\nA Start  1p  \n\n3p  1p  3p  Finish \r\n\r\nB Start  1s  \n\n3s  1s  3s  Finish \r\n\r\nC Start  1p  \n\n2p  3p  1p - Finish \r\n\r\nD Start  1s  \n\n2s  3s  1s - Finish \r\n\r\nE Start - 1p - \n\n1Ap(offset) - 3p - 1p - 1Ap(offset) - Finish \r\n\r\nF Start - 1s - \n\n1As(offset) - 3s - 1s - 1As(offset) - Finish \r\n\r\n&nbsp; \r\n\r\nMARK \n\nDESCRIPTION \r\n\r\nStart  The \n\nstarting line will be between a staff displaying an orange and yellow\nstriped \n\nflag on the starting line signal boat and an orange round buoy. \r\n\r\n1  Large \n\norange mark set as a windward mark \r\n\r\n1A   Small \n\norange buoy set as a current offset mark \r\n\r\n2   Large \n\norange buoy set as a reach mark \r\n\r\n3  Large \n\norange buoy set as a leeward mark set to leeward of the starting line \r\n\r\nFinish  The \n\nfinish line will be between a staff displaying an orange and yellow\nstriped \n\nflag on a Race Committee boat and an orange round buoy. 