INSERT INTO txt VALUES (81,'(Emailed to fleet on 6/21/04) \r\n\r\nHey Fleet, \r\n\r\nAnother great Thursday night of racing this week! For those who\ncouldnt make it out, we had 22 boats on the line and managed to\ncomplete 7 races  6 of which were long two lappers. Thanks to Liz &\nJim for running a great night of races. Ken/Page and Nick/Betsy\ncontinue to bring their Thursday night speed to the races, and the\nrest of us have been locked in some very close racing  3rd thru 9th\nplaces last night were separated by less than 20 points. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWere almost half-way through the summers Thursday night series, and\nthere are a few issues that I think we need to address to continue\nimproving and to make the next 12 weeks even better than the past 10.\nNows your chance to weigh in on these, or other, issues on fleet\norganization. A virtual town hall, if you will. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(1) Safety: This season has (knock on wood) been relatively\ndrama-free. Weve launched two R/C & safety boats each night, which I\nthink is imperative to respond quickly when capsizes/breakdowns\nbecome safety risks. I do think we need to be quicker to mobilize the\nextra safety boat when things go wrong. Last Thursday, Nick again\ntook the Navy SEAL plunge into the water to aide a competitor in\nrighting a turtled boat. Thanks to Nick, and a heads-up to the rest\nof us. The designated safety chair (usually the same as the social\nchair for that night) is responsible sailing to the dock and\nmobilizing the second crash boat if no extra hands are available to\ndo it (or if the wind is blowing sustained 15+ kts). If you miss any\nraces for safety related reasons, youll be scored average points\nfrom the races you have run for that night  if you have to operate\nthe safety boat all night, youll get your average finish from the\noverall Thursday night series. Bottom line, safety is priority, and\nyou wont be penalized for doing the safe thing. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThat said, Id also like to put in a word for individual\nresponsibility. For those without a ton of dinghy experience, keep in\nmind that the Vanguard can be a very challenging boat in heavy breeze\n a lot of fun, but challenging. If youre unsure about the\nconditions on a night, consider waiting 30 minutes or so until the\nwind backs off. If you get out on the water & flip a few times\n(particularly if youre having trouble self-righting the boat)\nconsider sailing back to the dock. You can get cold & tired easily,\neven with proper wetsuits, which it goes without saying that everyone\nshould wear. If youre intent on sailing and getting big breeze\nexperience, tie a sealed plastic milk jug to the top of your mainsail\n(thread the halyard thru the jug handle before you tie it to the head\nof the sail, raise them together to the top of the mast). This will\nkeep you from turtling, and thus from getting your mast stuck in the\nmud. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Race management: Liz & friends have helped us get lots of races\nin each night. Two issues in this bucket that we need to discuss are\nstarting rules (i.e., 1 minute rule) and course types/lengths. \r\n\r\n First, on the 1 minute rule, a few weeks ago Liz raised the concern\nthat it was sometimes difficult to get clean starts (w/o general\nrecalls) and that use of the 1 minute rule for all starts could help\nclean things up. This is a departure from our standard fleet practice\nwhich is (veterans, please correct me if I get this wrong) no\nrestrictions (no 1 minute rule, etc) on starts unless theres a\ngeneral recall. If so, next start is a 1-minute rule. If that\nproduces a second general recall, third start is black flag (youre\nover = youre out). After a clean start (i.e., when the next race is\nrun) we revert back to no restrictions. Im personally in favor of\nthe way wed done things historically, but think we should give\ndiscretion to the R/C to run things as he/she needs to keep the fleet\nfrom getting to aggressive at the line. Those with opinions, please\nweigh in. In the end, the decision goes to the R/C on how to run\nstarts, but we should discuss and then clarify in writing (via this\nmailing list) the rules wed like to follow. \r\n\r\n Second, weve used a variety of course lengths and finishes (upwind\n& reaching). I personally enjoy the variety, and with a bias towards\nthe reaching finishes when theres enough breeze to plane across the\nline and a bias to upwind finishes when its a lighter, shiftier day\nwhere tacking duels and passes are possible on the last upwind leg.\nOther thoughts? \r\n\r\n Third, Liz had talked about using a dry erase board on the R/C boat\nto display course type & other starting info. This week, we were\nstymied by lack of dry erase markers, but going forward well use\nthis to help on-the-water communication. It would be expected that\nall racers sailed by and read the board before a race, so this would\nbe a place the R/C could announce course changes, standing 1 minute\nrule, etc... Along those lines, we need to get the loud hailer back\nup and running for on the water communication & especially premature\nstarter calls. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n(3) Launching: This is my rant: Since weve had so many boats showing\nup each week, Ive seen major congestion occurring on the launch\nramp. A couple weeks ago, Wheeler & I (along with several others)\nmissed the first race because the launch ramp was backed up for 10\nminutes+. Im certain this wasnt the first or last time that\nhappened to some in the fleet. The solution to this is based in all\nof us stepping up our launching etiquette. The backup seems to begin\nwhen 3-4 boats are tied onto the launching dock for more than the\ncouple of minutes it should take to raise sails & go. Other boats\nthat are ready to launch (and to sail out to the course) get stuck,\nand we have a traffic jam bigger than the Bay Bridge at rush hour.\nHeres my etiquette proposal, others please chime in: \r\n\r\n Before you roll your boat down the ramp, make sure everything\npossible is set on your rigging. Jib up, main halyard attached & sail\nfed into the mast, outhaul attached and tightened, tack pin secure,\nmaximum slack set into the vang. \r\n\r\n Launch your boat w/ skipper & crew, both ready to sail (w/\nlifejacket, water, etc) \r\n\r\n Move your boat to the farthest space you can (usually 3 boats can be\nheld by the bow on the leeward part of the launch dock + 1 boat\nparallel parked at the end of the launch drop-in. When one boat\nlaunches, everybody can move down one spot to make room for the next\nboat. Please do this automatically. \r\n\r\n One person from the NEXT boat to waiting to launch goes down to grab\nthe empty dolly and takes it back up to the dolly pile. This allows\nthe launched boat skipper/crew to start raising sails & getting off\nthe dock quickly. \r\n\r\n Raise sails, put on your blades, and go. If you wait on the dock for\na few minutes because you want to head out at the last minute before\nstarting sequence, then everyone behind you will leave AFTER the last\nminute (i.e., theyll be late). This sucks for them, and sucks for\nyou if the next time you get stuck behind the clog. From the time\nyour boat hits the water, it shouldnt take more than 2 or 3 minutes\nto raise the mainsail, set the rudder/centerboard, and hit the water.\nSince theres space for 4 boats on the launch ramp dock (3+1 parallel\nparked) we should be able to put a new boat in the water every 30-60\nseconds. At that rate, everyone can make the first race & no one has\nto sail around for more than 10-15 minutes before the first gun. \r\n\r\nIf everyone does their parts (and reminds others to do theirs),\nthings will work much more smoothly & well be able to get 20+ boats\non the water in time for the first start. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOthers, please add comments on the above, or add topics that you feel\nare important to raise, with email replies to the list. Mike &\nRebecca, anything youve seen as Thursday Night Series chairs to\nadd/emphasize? Thanks to everyone for getting the season off to such\na strong start. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nChad \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPS  Id like to take this moment to acknowledge the exceptional\ncontributions of Mike & Rebecca whove been putting a ton of work\ninto planning and organizing the Thursday series. Next time you see\nthem, buy them a beer, give them a big hug (optional), and ask what\nyou can do to help! If you havent been social/safety chair yet, ask\nif there are any empty weeks to fill. If you have 5 minutes of extra\ntime at TISC, see if any help is needed launching/storing R/C boats,\netc \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n');
