INSERT INTO txt VALUES (370,'1. RULES \r\n\r\n1.1 The regatta will be governed by the rules as defined in The\nRacing Rules of Sailing (2005-2008), the prescriptions of the United\nStates Sailing Association and the Vanguard 15 Class rules, except\nwhere modified by these sailing instructions. \r\n\r\n1.2 Racing rule 40.1 will be changed as follows: personal floatation\ndevices (PFDs) must be worn at all times while sailing\n(dock-to-dock). \r\n\r\n1.3 The following are highlighted to ensure safety on the race\ncourse: \r\n\r\n(a) All boats are required to have an attached bow-line (painter) of\n20+ feet while sailing. This clarifies rule 1.2. \r\n\r\n(b) Alcohol consumption and substance use is prohibited while sailing\n(dock-to-dock). This clarifies rule 5. \r\n\r\n(c) Competitors are encouraged to assist other boats in distress or\nbe on standby assistance if another competitor is in the water. Boats\nthat assist are eligible for scoring redress upon request to the PRO.\nRules 1.1, 60.1, and 62.1(c). \r\n\r\n\r\n2. ELIGIBILITY, ENTRY & FEES \r\n\r\n2.1 The regatta is open to all boats of the Vanguard 15, Laser, and\nLaser Radial classes. \r\n\r\n2.2 Eligible boats may enter by completing a Registration Form, a\nTISC Medical & Liability Form for each sailor, and paying entry fees. \r\n\r\n(a) Vanguard 15s must designate which division in which they will\ncompete. \r\n- Collegiate skippers shall register their boat for the Varsity division\r\n- Non-collegiate skippers may choose either Varsity or Junior Varsity  \r\n\r\n2.3 Required entry fees will be paid to the Race Chairs or Vanguard\n15 Treasurer. \r\n\r\n(a) Entry fees are $100 for the season or $15 per night. \r\n\r\n(b) Additional visitor fees apply to competitors who are non-TISC\ntenants. These fees ($10/night) are paid directly to TISC. \r\n\r\n2.4 Boats that race five (5) or more nights will be assigned Social\nChair duties by the Race Chairs. \r\n\r\n\r\n3. NOTICES TO COMPETITORS \r\n\r\n3.1 Notices to competitors shall be posted to the fleet website\n(ww.vanguard15.org) on the Regatta sign-up page for which that\nnotice applies before 3:00pm on the day it shall take effect. \r\n\r\n3.2 Notices to competitors may be posted on the official notice\nboard, located across from TISC clubhouse door, before 6:00pm on the\nday it shall take effect. \r\n\r\n\r\n4. CHANGES TO SAILING INSTRUCTIONS \r\n\r\n4.1 Any change to the sailing instructions shall be posted on the\nfleet website (www.vanguard15.org) on the page entitled Messages\nbefore 3:00pm on the day it shall take effect. This changes rule\n89.2(c). \r\n\r\n4.2 Any change to the sailing instruction may be posted on the\nofficial notice board before 6:00pm on the day it shall take effect. \r\n\r\n\r\n5. ANNOUNCEMENTS MADE ASHORE \r\n\r\n5.1 Any announcement made ashore will be made at 6:00pm in the area\nbetween the official notice board and TISC clubhouse door. \r\n\r\n\r\n6. SCHEDULE OF RACES \r\n\r\n6.1 Registration will be open from 5:45-6:00pm each night of racing. \r\n\r\n6.2 Twenty-three (23) Thursday nights are scheduled for the series\nfrom the first Thursday in April to the first Thursday in September\n(i.e., April 6 September 7, 2006). \r\n\r\n6.3 Five (5) or more races will be attempted each night for each\nclass. \r\n\r\n6.4 The warning signal for the first race is 6:30pm (sharp). \r\n\r\n6.5 No race shall be started after sunset. \r\n\r\n\r\n7. CLASS FLAGS \r\n\r\nNo class flags will be used. \r\n\r\n\r\n8. RACING AREA \r\n\r\n8.1 The racing area will be located within the confines of Clipper\nCove, between Treasure Island and Yerba Buena Island. \r\n\r\n8.2 All Vanguard 15s & Lasers are required to keep a safe distance\nfrom other boats who are anchored, docked or underway in Clipper Cove\nat all times, racing or not. Failure to do so may result in an\nassigned DSQ by the PRO. DSQ appeals for racing area violations will\nnot be permitted. \r\n\r\n\r\n9. THE COURSES \r\n\r\n9.1 The courses will be a modified windward-leeward (W/L) of 1-2 laps\nrounding to port, unless otherwise announced by the race committee. \r\n\r\n(a) Modified is a start/finish line between the windward and leeward\nmarks with a windward leg finish. \r\n\r\n9.2 Unless announced, the following race will be the same course as\nthe prior race. \r\n\r\n9.3 The start/finish line will not be restricted, unless indicated by\nthe race committee. \r\n\r\n(a) A restricted start/finish line may be implemented when five or\nmore Lasers are competing. \r\n\r\n9.4 Finished boats are requested to stay clear of the finishing area\nuntil the following race sequence is underway. \r\n\r\n9.5 Courses will not be shortened. Any race that is deemed an unfair\ntest of skill by the race committee will be canceled and restarted at\ntheir discretion. This changes rule 32. \r\n\r\n9.6 Legs of the course will not be changed after the preparatory\nsignal. Any race that is deemed an unfair test of skill by the race\ncommittee will be canceled and restarted at their discretion. This\nchanges rule 33. \r\n\r\n\r\n10. MARKS \r\n\r\n10.1 Marks will be small inflatable orange spheres, unless otherwise\nannounced. \r\n\r\n10.2 The starting and finishing marks will consist of an orange\nsphere at the port end and the race committee boat at the starboard\nend. \r\n\r\n\r\n11. THE START \r\n\r\n11.1 Races will be started using the Sound-Signal Starting System\n(Appendix Q). Audible signals shall govern. No visual signals will be\nused. A series of short signals will be made before the sequence\nbegins in order to attraction attention. This changes rule 26. \r\n\r\n11.2 The starting line will be between the orange ball pin and the\nTISC flag displayed on the race committee boat. \r\n\r\n11.3 The starting sequence shall consist of the following sound\nsignals made at the indicated times: \r\n\r\n-(Warning)	3 long	@ 3 minutes\r\n-(Preparatory)	2 long	@ 2 minutes\r\n- 	1 long, 3 short	@ 1 minute, 30 seconds\r\n- 	1 long	@ 1 minute\r\n-	3 short	@ 30 seconds\r\n- 	2 short	@ 20 seconds\r\n- 	1 short	@ 10 seconds\r\n- 	1 short	@ 5,4,3,2,1 seconds\r\n-(Starting)	1 long	@ 0 seconds\r\n\r\n11.4 Individual recalls may be identified by the race committee using\naudible or visual signals. \r\n\r\n(a) Race committee will attempt to signal boats that have started\nprematurely by hailing sail numbers and raising the X code flag\n(blue cross on white background); however, it is the responsibility\nof the competitors to start correctly. This changes rule 29.1. \r\n\r\n(b) No redress will be granted for failure to hear an individual\nrecall hail, failure to see the X flag displayed, or failure of the\nrace committee to make any signal. This changes rule 62.1(a). \r\n\r\n11.5 General recalls shall be signaled by multiple whistle blasts\nfollowing a start. A new sequence will be started immediately\nfollowing a general recall. This changes rule 29.2. \r\n\r\n(a) At the race committees discretion, the One Minute Rule may be\nput into effect using either the I code flag (black circle on\nyellow background) or by announcement. When the One Minute Rule is in\neffect, any boat that crosses the start line AFTER the one minute\nsignal but prior to the starting signal, will be required to sail\naround (i.e. round) one end of the starting line (pin or RC boat)\nbefore starting or will be scored OCS. This changes rule 30.1. \r\n\r\n(b) Race committee will attempt to cleanly start the Vanguard 15\nfleet before starting the next Laser race. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n12. THE FINISH \r\n\r\n12.1 The finish line will be the same as the starting line (between\nthe orange ball pin and the TISC flag displayed on the race committee\nboat). \r\n\r\n(a) Race committee has the right to assign finishing positions\nwithout signaling or announcing it will do so. \r\n\r\n(b) The next race shall be started promptly following the finish of\nthe last competitor of the current race or by the decision of the\nrace committee. \r\n\r\n\r\n13. PENALTY SYSTEM \r\n\r\n13.1 Competitors that commit a foul during a race shall exonerate\nthemselves by taking a One-Turn Penalty (1 turn in same direction\nwith 1 tack & 1 gybe) when two or more boat lengths from any mark.\nThis changes rule 44.1 and 44.2. \r\n\r\n13.2 If the foul is committed within the two-boat lengths circle of\nany mark, including the starting pin and race committee boat, a\nTwo-Turns Penalty (2 turns in same direction with 2 tacks & 2 gybes)\nis required to exonerate a boat. This changes rule 44.1. \r\n\r\n13.3 Competitors may not take a Scoring Penalty. This changes rule\n44.3. \r\n\r\n\r\n14. PROTESTS AND REQUESTS FOR REDRESS \r\n\r\n14.1 A competitor is required to hail Protest (sail number)\nimmediately after the incident/foul if the competitor intends to file\na protest. (Saying, Do your circles is not adequate.) This changes\nrule 61.1(a). \r\n\r\n14.2 Upon finishing the race, the competitor (protestor) is required\nto inform the race committee and the offending boat (protestee) that\nthey intend to proceed with a protest. (State: Boat #___ protests\nboat #____.) This changes rule 61.2. \r\n\r\n14.3 Protests will be conducted using the 3 Minute Justice System.\nThis changes rule 63. \r\n\r\n(a) Upon the completion of racing, each party of the protest selects\none competitor as a jury member. The two appointed jury members then\nselect a third competitor to complete the Protest Committee. This\nchanges rule 90. \r\n\r\n(b) Each party is given three (3) minutes to present their view of\nthe incident and the applicable rules. After presenting, the party\nmay call one witness to further substantiate their position. \r\n\r\n(c) After both parties have presented, the Protest Committee will\ndecide the outcome and inform both the involved parties and race\ncommittee. \r\n\r\n(d) All decisions of the Protest Committee are final. \r\n\r\n\r\n14.4 Competitors requesting redress may do after all races are\ncompleted. The request should be made verbally to the race committee.\nThis changes rule 62. \r\n\r\n(a) If redress is granted, the requesting boat will typically receive\naverage points for the race in question. Average points will be\ncalculated by averaging the finishing positions for all other races\nsailed that night and awarding that calculated position for the race\nin question. Rule A10(a). \r\n\r\n\r\n15. SCORING \r\n\r\n15.1 Boats that have not registered, paid, or signed in will not be\nscored. \r\n\r\n(a) All boats must sign in with the Race Chairs each night sailed. \r\n\r\n\r\n15.2 Nightly Scoring \r\n\r\n(a) The Low Point Scoring System will apply. \r\n- A boats finishing place is her race score: 1st place = 1 point, 2nd place = 2 points, etc.  A boats Series Score is the sum of all her race scores.\r\n\r\n(b) Two (2) races are required to be completed to constitute a\nseries. \r\n\r\n(c) No scores will be excluded (all races count). This changes rule\nA2. \r\n\r\n(d) A boat that did not finish (DNF) shall be scored a last place\nfinish. More than one boat may be scored a last place finish. This\nchanges rule A4.2. \r\n\r\n(e) A boat that did not start (DNS), was disqualified (DSQ), retired\nafter finishing (RAF) or was on-the-course-side/over-early (OCS)\nshall be scored a last place finish plus 1 point. This changes rule\nA4.2. \r\n\r\n(f) If calculations of the Series Score result in boats tied, each\nboats race scores shall be listed in order of best to worst. At the\nfirst point where there is a difference, the tie shall be broken in\nfavor of the boat with the best score. If no difference occurs, the\nboats shall be scored as a tie. This changes rule A8.2. \r\n\r\n(g) The Race Chairs are responsible for calculating and announcing\nthe evenings series scores. The Race Chairs, at their discretion,\nmay assign this task to another individual. \r\n\r\n\r\n15.3 Series Scoring \r\n\r\n(a) The High Point System will apply. \r\n\r\n(b) A boats overall finish for each evening will count as one race\nfor the overall Thursday Night Series standings. \r\n- A boats nightly Series Score will earn a High Point Score equal to the total number of boats that started at least one race on that night.  (For example, if 20 boats began at least one race, then the 1st place boat would earn 20 points, the 2nd place boat would earn 19 points, etc.)\r\n\r\n(c) Bonus Points will be awarded for nightly participation. \r\n- Five (5) points shall be added to each High Point Score if a registered boat is sailed by at least one registered team member.\r\n\r\n(d) If a boat is sailed by competitors from different registered\nboats, the evenings High Point Score and Bonus Points will be\nawarded to the registered boat whos sail number was used for racing\nthat night. \r\n\r\n(e) Only a boats 12 highest High Point Scores will be used to\ncalculate the overall Thursday Night Series standings. \r\n- Note: The website site will show the cumulative Thursday Night Series standings in the lower right corner of the homepage, which may include more than 12 scores.\r\n\r\n(f) The Race Chairs are responsible for posting High Point Scores to\nthe fleets website (www.vanguard15.org) in a timely manner. The Race\nChairs, at their discretion, may assign this task to another\nindividual. \r\n\r\n\r\n16. BOAT STORAGE \r\n\r\n16.1 All boats must be properly stored in their assigned storage\nspace (rack or dolly/trailer) at the end of each night. Return all\ndollies to the proper storage area. Sails and blades stored in the\nsail loft should be left in an orderly fashion. \r\n\r\n\r\n17. COMPETITOR RESPONSIBILITIES \r\n\r\n17.1 Competitors shall assist the Race Committee in the launch and\nstorage of the RC and chase boats, marks, and other equipment. \r\n\r\n\r\n17.2 Competitors shall assist the Social Chairs in the closing down\nof the facility, including the locking down of the cranes, closing of\nthe fences, storage of the bridals, coiling of the hoses, picking up\nof trash, etc. \r\n\r\n(a) Bottle caps need to be thrown into the garbage, not onto the\nground. \r\n\r\n(b) Trash bins shall be placed outside the main gate and the main\ngate locked at the end of the night. \r\n\r\n\r\n17.3 Social Chair duties include acting as the Safety Chair during\nracing and providing post-racing beverages and snacks. The Social\nChair may need to abandon racing and use the chase boat to help boats\nin distress. \r\n\r\n\r\n18. RACE COMMITTEE \r\n\r\n18.1 The race committee shall consist of two or more individuals. One\nindividual will be designated the Primary Race Officer (PRO) by the\nRace Chairs. \r\n\r\n18.2 The PRO shall be in charge of racing that night. The PRO will\ndecide on placement of the marks, which course to race, and any other\nrelevant decisions. \r\n\r\n19. PRIZES \r\n\r\n19.1 Varsity Division. Prizes will be awarded based on overall\nstandings to the boats in first, second and third place. Two prizes\nper boat will be awarded. \r\n\r\n19.2 Junior Varsity Division. Prizes will be awarded based on overall\nstandings to the boat in first place if the division has <= 5 boats.\nTwo prizes per boat will be awarded. \r\n\r\n(a) If the division has 6-7 boats, prizes will be awarded to first\nand second place. \r\n\r\n(b) If the division has 8 or more boats, then prizes will be awarded\nto first, second and third place. \r\n\r\n19.3 Participation Awards will be defined and awarded by the Race\nChairs and Fleet Captain to any competitor. \n\n19.4 All prizes will be awarded at the annual meeting held after the\nHoliday Classic in December. \r\n\r\n\r\n20. DISCLAIMER OF LIABILITY \n\nCompetitors participate in the regatta entirely of their own risk.\nSee rule 4, Decision to Race. The organizing authority will not\naccept any liability for material damage or personal injury or death\nsustained in conjunction with or prior to, during, or after the\nregatta. ');
